<p classD"MsoNormal" styleD"textautospace:none"<u<span styleD"font
size:18.0pt"Abstract:&nbsp;</span</u<span styleD"fontsize:18.0pt"<o
:p</o:p</span</p
<p classD"MsoNormal" styleD"textautospace:none"<span styleD"fontsi
ze:18.0pt"Viscoelasticity, a ubiquitous material property, can be tuned to
 engineer a wide range of fascinating applications such as mechanical dampe
rs, artificial tissues, functional foams
 and optoelectronics, among others. In this work, atomistic mechanisms resp
onsible for viscoelastic damping in various inorganic solids have been stud
ied using molecular dynamics simulations. Oscillatory shear deformation sim
ulations at a wide range of shear
 frequencies spanning several decades serve as a powerful probe to elucidat
e atomistic mechanisms for damping. In crystalline composites consisting of
 a stiff inclusion in a soft matrix, exceptional damping (up to 20 times la
rger than theoretical bounds) can
 be attained and can be tuned by modifying the microstructure, inclusion fr
action and elastic properties of the components. The primary reason for the
 damping is due to large anharmonicity in phononphonon coupling, resulting
 from the composite microstructure.
 Extending our analysis to structures with marked difference in their cryst
allinity, namely, ordered, random and glassy alloys, we demonstrate distinc
t damping mechanisms that depend on vibrational properties of the material 
at high frequencies (of the order
 of THz). At lower frequencies (down to MHz), a unique channel for damping 
via long timescale structural relaxation is observed in the glassy alloy. 
This property is, in fact, observed in a wide range of glasses, signifying 
damping characteristics in glass
 to be universal in nature. Theoretical understanding gained in this work w
ill help design novel materials for highfrequency damping applications.<o:
p</o:p</span</p
